### Finishing

I wanted the natural walnut to be on display, so I didn't apply any stain. I
finished the credenza with three coats of [General Finishes Arm-R-Seal gloss
urethane
topcoat](https://generalfinishes.com/wood-finishes-retail/oil-based-topcoats/arm-r-seal-oil-based-topcoat).
Before the first coat, I sanded meticulously with 150 grit sandpaper, then I
sanded with 320 and 400 grit between the second and third coats. I mostly
followed the techniques from [this video](https://youtu.be/iPtoPBMbAP8),
applying with cotton cloths and sanding between each coat, then wiping off and
applying mineral spirits before applying the stain.

I hadn't mentioned the legs yet. Since I don't own a lathe, I opted to buy
[these pre-fabbed
legs](https://www.tablelegs.com/mccobb-mid-century-modern-feet-straight-cleat-set-4-feet-2-cleats/)
from tablelegs.com in walnut with an 8" length. They were pretty pricey at $145
(after 20% discount), but they are high quality and were the only nice walnut
legs I could find. I also liked that they come with a cleat for added
stability.

